{"id":"2003.01833","submitter":"Nathan Vaughn","authors":"Nathan Vaughn, Vikram Gavini, Robert Krasny","title":"Treecode-accelerated Green Iteration for Kohn-Sham Density Functional\n  Theory","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.jcp.2020.110101","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.comp-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a real-space computational method called treecode-accelerated\nGreen Iteration (TAGI) for all-electron Kohn-Sham Density Functional Theory.\nTAGI is based on a reformulation of the Kohn-Sham equations in which the\neigenvalue problem in differential form is converted into a fixed-point problem\nin integral form by convolution with the modified Helmholtz Green's function.\nIn each self-consistent field (SCF) iteration, the fixed-points are computed by\nGreen Iteration, where the discrete convolution sums are efficiently evaluated\nby a GPU-accelerated barycentric Lagrange treecode. Other techniques used in\nTAGI include adaptive mesh refinement, Fej\\'er quadrature, singularity\nsubtraction, gradient-free eigenvalue update, and Anderson mixing to accelerate\nconvergence of the SCF and Green Iterations. Ground state energy computations\nof several atoms (Li, Be, O) and small molecules (H$_2$, CO, C$_6$H$_6$)\ndemonstrate TAGI's ability to efficiently achieve chemical accuracy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Mar 2020 23:28:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 5 Mar 2020 12:17:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-24"}
